<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. NEIL SOLOMON: CANCER RISKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: If a woman has a genital herpes infection, does that mean she is more 
likely to get genital cancer? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Infection with the herpes simplex virus does appear to be associated 
with the development of genital cancer in women; however, this does not 
necessarily mean there is a cause-and-effect relationship between the two 
events. Some authorities attribute the development of genital cancer in these 
women to the risk of frequent sexual activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
