<HEADLINE>
<P>
WOMAN SURVIVES FOR 20 DAYS ON LIFE RAFT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A woman survived 20 days adrift in a rubber life raft after her boat hit a reef 
and sank in a storm, officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Claudine Pare, 42, of Noumea, New Caledonia, washed ashore in the raft on 
remote Tanga Island, in the far northeast of Papua New Guinea, on June 19. It 
took nine days for word of her plight to reach Port Moresby, the national 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
Pare bought the yacht, Excitable Boy, in New Zealand and sailed alone from 
Auckland on May 12 for New Caledonia. She said the boat hit a reef during a 
storm on May 30 and sank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
