<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lotus Wins Copyright Suit: A federal court judge in Boston ruled that the 
keyboard commands and on-screen images of the company's top-selling 1-2-3 
spreadsheet software program for the personal computer are protected by 
copyright laws. 
</P>
<P>
Paperback Software International, which plans to appeal the ruling, argued that 
the copyright applies only to the inner workings of the software, and that the 
commands represented only instructions for the machine. Similar issues have 
been raised in a spate of other "look and feel" lawsuits involving the 
appearance and operations of PC software. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA062990-0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 240581 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 29, 1990, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
